Introduction
Poverty is inextricably connected with global healthcare inequalities. According to the World Bank (2008) report, about 1.5 billion people live below the poverty line. For poor people, poverty deprives them of their human dignity and denies them access to quality healthcare opportunities. The poor are often prone to ill health, HIV/AIDS, and undernourishment due to lack of income and expensive care costs. Moreover, most of the world‚Äôs poor endures intense physical labor, unhealthy diet, and environmental risks that pose a threat to their health.
